Note: jst connectors used in cable hub and cables are soldered to a small strip of pcb

Update 2017-Oct-29 :
1) Updated static base for stability
2) New chain ends
3) Chain segment and braces here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2607130, choose appropriate chain brace for the number of cables you will mount to the cable chain

This is to tidy up the cables and connectors after installing the hanging blower: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2473423

The chain segment is remixed from: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:11978 I wanted them to be as small as possible so the cables fit snug. I used 18 pieces of the segments

This mod requires cutting and lengthening (about a foot) the existing cables. Cut near the connector end. Before cutting, label the fan and blower cables, the thermistor and heater cables are non-directional.

The tiny screws to attach the chain ends to the bases are from a dead laptop, they are 5-6mm long. DO NOT use anything longer as they may hit the rubber rollers.

The static base is mounted 17cm from the right aluminum bar, I used the extra bolt/nut that came with the printer to mount it to the x aluminum bar, one is longer so I used the washer with it.

Assembly overview:
1) Connect the cable segments, play with it for awhile to loosen them up.
2) Screw end1 to the active base, end2 to the static base
3) Mark fan cables and cut them
4) Insert cables into the chain assembly
5) Install the active base to the roller assembly, it should snap in, use one of the stock fan screw to secure it along with a washer
6) Install the static base 17cm from the right bar
7) Install xz cable holder
8) Arrange cable and connectors (if you use one) and install the active base cover
9) Lengthen and splice the cables

This function returns the gray code representation of the supplied bit count.

Gray code is useful in that it is a binary representation of values where only one bit changes at a time as the represented number increases. This allows reliable sensing of magnets or holes for linear or rotary encoders.

The function supports bit counts from 2 to 8 and is hard coded.

This thing is an attempt to make a printable version of the "Toy Siren Whistle", patented in 1934 by J. Lauterbach. (pat # 1,955,815).

1) WH3 and WH5 form the internal rotor. Glue them together with acetone.
2) WH1 is the mouth piece. It should fit snugly with the casing (WH4)
3) Insert 693 ball bearings in the sockets inside WH4 and WH2.
4) Insert the rotor and mount the end pieced (WH2)
5) Apply a pair of high capacity lungs - or power it with an alternate source of pressurised air. Make sure that the rotor can spin freely before mounting the end cap. try sanding the inside of the rotor blades if it doesn't spin. PS. The current version requires a powerful airstream to operate, but it makes quite a distinctive sound (download sound.m4a to listen to it)

description.text:
As you can see from the extended sine and cosine graphs, each curve repeats itself regularly. This trait is called "periodicity", because there is a "period" over which the curve repeats itself over and over. The length of the period for the sine and cosine curves is clearly 2π: "once around" a circle. Also, each of sine and cosine vary back and forth between –1 and +1. The curves go one unit above and below their midlines (here, the x-axis). This value of "1" is called the "amplitude".

When you graph, don't try to plot loads of points. Note that the cosine is at y = 1 when x = 0 and 2π; at y = 0 for x = π/2 and 3π/2, and at y = –1 for x = π. Plot these five "interesting" points, and then fill in the curve.

description.text:
This is a reusable fastener that I designed in Sketchup that secures a bicycleâ€™s brake and shift cables to the frameâ€™s cable housing fittings. Most of the time when people secure their bicycleâ€™s brake and shift cables to the frame they use a small zip-tie. One day while talking to my bicycle mechanic friend he mentioned that Shimano makes some specific cable housing clips that you can use instead of using a zip tie. He showed me one and I asked if I could have it. He scoffed and quickly took it back from me. As he described it supposedly these clips are hard to come by and more expensive than they need to be for what they are, a small piece of plastic. A perfect task for a 3D printer! What was my response? â€œFine, Iâ€™ll print my own.â€ I do not know how universal cable housings are on bikes. I think they might be pretty uniform because the brake and shift cables are a standardized diameter.
For specifics this fits the four cable housings on my 2010 Cannondale rz One Twenty mountain bike. This bike is awesome by the way. For this fastener I needed the tolerances to be extremely close so that the cable cannot vibrate between the housing and the fastener. This could cause chafing of the cable and in general it is annoying to hear cables slapping around on your bicycle. Due to the small tolerances required it took me many prints and revisions to achieve the final design that I am happy and proud of. Normally when making a small part from scratch it takes me about 7 â€“ 10 prints before Iâ€™m satisfied, this project took me 38 attempts. It took so many prints because of the importance that the fastener snap very rigidly and securely into place and that there be no gap between the cable and fastener. Additionally, I like these last five things about the fastener:
1) It is reusable, whereas the zip-tie approach is not because you have to cut it off.
2) The fastener also snaps onto the cable so that when you are working on your bike you can detach the cable from the housing, but the clip is still attached to the cable. This means you wonâ€™t lose the clip.
3) More polished and professional looking than a zip-tie. Zip-ties are in the same family as bungee cords, extremely functional but not super attractive.
4) Functional bragging rights around the guys on the trail ïŠ
5) It complements the engineering of my bike. Seriously, my bike is an engineering marvel, what better way to accompany its engineering successes?

Note: Expect it to take a fair amount of force to get the fastener to snap into place. To be very secure and not fall off, ever, means it can be a struggle to get it into position. First print the fastener then align the cable into the housing channel and then slide fastener over the top of the cable until legs snap into place on the underside of the housing. It is very important that the cable is lying in the groove of the housing before you try to get the fastener in place. The cable acts as a spreader and opens the legs of the clip just enough so that the legs get around the housing. You may need to scale up or down the model depending on your 3D printer.

title: BCN3D Sigma Stock Hotend Cover - Pimp Your Hotend

description.text:
This is a custom cover and output vent for the BCN3D Sigma, to replace the stock white metal covers which go over the hotend assembly.

For those conscious about weight, these are about 14g, compared to the stock metal ones being about 33g, not including screws/fans etc.

Uses Stock Fans, and all the metal framing around the stock hotends, and Stock bolts.
You will however need and additional 2x M3 x 12 bolts, to hold the output vent onto the main cover.
You can use the 3 main fan bolts to bolt the fan back on, leaving 1 bolt hole unpopulated, or alternatively use 1 of the stock bolts in the top corner which holds this cover to the metal frame, and the other 3 bolts are additional M3 x 16. This is optional though, as the 3 stock bolts work fine, just protrude through a little bit.

Main fan needs to be unplugged from the fan PCB, which just involves removing the back plastic cover, and unplugged it, threading it through and plugging it back in again.

Best printed upside down with a small support.
Vent is best printed so the flat output face is down.
You will need to rotate the STL's to suit.

I printed these in ABS so they would stand up to hotend temperatures for a decent amount of time. PLA may be fine, but I have not tried it. If using the fans, then the plastic should not get too warm at all.

High detail STL's included.
If you need lower detail, let me know.

title: Pebble Time Round 14mm Pocket Watch
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a pocket watch shell for the Pebble Time round with 14mm band (the small one). It uses one of the quick-release spring bars from the watch band as hinge.
The pattern on the lid is the maze from the TV show "Westworld". I also included a blank lid for you to design as you like.

For assembly: Remove watch bands and clip the watch body in the bottom shell. Remove one spring bar from the watchband and put it in the hinge of the lid. To do so, the small support part at the beginning of the slit where the tiny handle goes has to be removed with a knife.

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.1mm

Infill:

100%

Notes:

Its a bit of a difficult print - especially the hinge. The walls are designed for a 0.4mm nozzle but maybe a smaller one will be even better.

Print both shells with support and outside surface on top for best surface finish.
Printing with the flat side on the printbed did not work for me because of small islands and overhang (cooling problem and bad finish). But you can try ;-)

I did not use support inside the hinge hole. But if it fails, you could maybe use some and drill it out afterwards.

Sand it and paint it as you like. I used one coat of black spray-paint for the embossed lines on the lid and silver metallic paint for the rest. To not cover the black lines, I sprayed a paper towel with silver paint and pressed the lid to it multiple times. Another technique I read about after doing this is to applying a black coat over the silver one and whipe it down while still wet.

You could also use some metallic-fill PLA, spray the pattern black and sand and polish it afterwards. I did not try that yet though.

I used Autodesk Inventor (free student version) to design this thing. There are cad models for every pebble watch available at https://github.com/pebble/pebble-3d . That helped a lot for designing the cutouts!

For the maze I got an svg file from reddit
https://www.reddit.com/r/westworld/comments/5gro0o/vectorized_maze_image/
I had to import and extruded it in Fusion360 and then export and import again to Inventor. Inventor aparently has no option to import an svg sketch and even after a conversion to dwg it failed (open loops, could not extrude).

title: CR 10 Z Axis Manual Adjustment Knob and Bearing.

description.text:
Taken from idea by baschz.
It seems all CR-10 are not the same. The knob design by baschz did not fit my leadscrew. The Z axis bearing on his machine is different than mine too.
I have redesigned it and a completely new bearing so it will fit all printers.
The bearing block uses the same screws and Tee nuts as the original and you also need 2 M4 x 10mm screws and nuts. The bearing is mounted in a recess that is adjustable in the Y direction so it can be accurately set to your own printer allowing for any manufacturing tolerances.

Installation instructions.
Remove existing bearing and the ball bearing inside.
Push the 2 M4 nuts into the slots in the new part and fit the ball bearing.
Attach the plate with the 2 M4 screws but do not tighten them yet. this will allow the bearing to line up correctly with the leadscrew.
Fit the new block to the printer with the screws on the top and move the Z axis all the way to the top.
Tighten the screws. This will hold the bearing in the correct Y direction.
Home the axis and then remove the new bearing and refit with the screws facing downward. Adjust the block in the X direction and tighten the screws.
Fit the knob.

description.text:
Updated design 2018-02-12

This is a compact frame / shell for a brushless micro race drone with 2 inch propellers. I designed it for use with the Lizard95 electronics and motors in combination with the Runcam Micro Swift FPV camera and the Eachine ATX03 video transmitter.

Instead of buying a Lizard95 you can also use the Eachine Minicube Flytower 20x20 stack. The 3 bladed propellers on the photo's are Gemfan Hulkie 2040 props. They are a perfect fit.

  • The sound of the beeper is still loud from inside the casing.
  • Easy to use mounts for rubber bands to attach the battery.

Notes:

I have had the best results with PETG filament. Printed at 100% infill. Looks good and is strong. Survived a number of crashes already.

I have also tried ABS and Polycarbonate, but these were not that durable as the PETG version.

I have started learning 123D Design a few weeks ago. I had some experience with Wings 3D and was able to learn the basics pretty quickly. Ones I've got some skills I started designing.

I had a few goals:

  • I wanted to use the components of my Eachine Lizard95 and wanted to add a Runcam Micro Swift camera along with a ATX03 video transmitter to it.

  • I wanted the components to be protected against wet grass and dirt.

I started recreating the components that I wanted to use first. Then I started working on the frame. It took me a few nights to get to this design. Started from scratch multiple times.

description.text:
This is a simple model of a railway platform. The design includes a platform, roof, roof support poles, and a set of stairs. This platform is roughly scaled for O-scale (O27) trains (e.g. Lionel). As built, the platform sits 32-mm high and is 170-mm long and 50-mm wide. You may want to scale it so that the platform is at a different height. When printing the bridge for other scales, suggested scaling is:
  • for G (1:22.5), scale by about 200%
  • for regular O-scale, scale by 113%
  • for S, OK as is (i.e., 100%)
  • for HO, scale by 65% to 70%
  • for N, scale by 40% to 50%
  • for Z, scale by 40% to 45%

This is a simple model of a railway platform. This design is based on pictures on the internet and does not model a specific platform. This platform is roughly scaled for O-scale (O27) trains (e.g. Lionel). The design includes a platform, roof, roof support poles, and a set of stairs. As built, the platform sits 32-mm high and is 170-mm long and 50-mm wide. You may want to scale it so that the platform is at a different height. When printing the bridge for other scales, suggested scaling is:
  • for G (1:22.5), scale by about 200%
  • for regular O-scale, scale by 113%
  • for S, OK as is (i.e., 100%)
  • for HO, scale by 65% to 70%
  • for N, scale by 40% to 50%
  • for Z, scale by 40% to 45%
    • The dimensions of the stl files are:
  • overall height (including roof), 106 mm (4.17")
  • width 50 mm (1.97")
  • length 170-mm (6.69")
    • The design also includes a set of stairs. Two designs are provided: one with hand rails and one without hand rails. I was impressed that my Makerbot Replicaor2 successfully built the stairs with hand rails. The fullsize version of the design was printed on a Makerbor Replicator2
  • platform printed upside down.
  • roof printed rightside up.
  • separate builds for the body and roof
  • scaled by 100% (see recommendations above for scaling)
  • PLA (Makerbot filament)
  • Printed: standard resolution, 10% infill, 2 shells, 0.20 mm layer height, 230C
  • a raft was not used
  • the design requires good adhesion of the roof with the build plate.
  • the roof warped a little. i carefully used a heat gun to warm the plastic enough to bend it back into shape.
    • The only cleanup should be the stairs with hand rails. The roof must have good adhesion to the build plate. Otherwise, it's a simple build. Parts list: no additional items needed Assembly instructions: The posts are designed with rounded edges and are slightly undersized so they "should" fit snuggly with the platform and roof. Some fine tuning might be needed. Some best practices for printing:
  • optimize print parameters for your printer, filament, etc (only you can determine the best parameters)
  • use good filament
  • level your build plate prior to printing complex parts. it's worth the few minutes it takes. always level after removing tape, or if pulling hard to remove a part.
  • make sure the build plate is clean.
  • if using blue tape, stretch it tight when applying it to the build plate.
  • if you have small holes in the blue tape, the parts should still print without any problems.
  • pre-feed the filament 30 to 60-s before printing (i.e., run load for 30-60s)
  • do not print several complicated parts in one build (do complex parts by themselves)
  • I find that printing faster is better (probably so the filament can't ball up in one spot)
  • when the filament spool gets low, the filament can be tightly wound on the spool and the filament may not feed properly... take special care...
  • when a new spool is used, it is easy for the filament to jump outside the spool and then it will bind up later around the spool holder ruining your build
  • make sure it is easy for the filament to enter the filament feed tube. others have designed spools, mounts, etc. for that purpose. i use a small rope that forces the filament away from the spool before entering the filament feed tube.
  • make sure that there aren't any obstructions on the spool. many manufacturers feed the filament through holes in the side of the spool. make sure the material has been removed.
  • if you hear clicking when printing, that may be a result of the filament wrapped around the spool and not feeding
  • for the Makerbot replicator2, look at the blob a filament in the left front part of the build plate and then the trail of filament to the build location. there should be a glob, and the line of filament should be continuous and smooth
  • one way to remove parts when using blue tape is to use a very thin spatula bought in craft-art stores (advice from youtube). get one with a wide, blunt front end (not long and thin). mine is 11 mils thick (0.011") and 20-mm wide at the front. a painting spatula/scraper in hardware stores won't work and may damage the build plate. (I use blue tape so I don't have any best practices for bare plates, heated plates or for other tapes like mylar)
  • perform regular maintenance (grease, etc).
  • when I continued to have problems printing even after performing maintenance, following troublshooting instructions, changing filaments, cleaning gears, cleaning everything, optimizing print parameters, changing temperatures, etc., I bought a new extruder assembly from Makerbot and it solved all of my problems.

description.text:
These are the supporting files for the Learning Blade Lightweight Glider 3D Maker Quest.

This Maker Quest gives students practice designing a simple aircraft glider. The model files in this lesson can be modified, printed, and assembled into a glider. Students can also test and fly their glider designs, measuring and comparing their efficiency.
NGSS

Have you ever considered how aircraft are designed and tested? The search of faster, safer, and better air travel is constantly producing improvements to aircraft designs. An important step in the design process is testing.

Customizing the Gliders After downloading, the model files for the glider can be edited and customized. The individual files for the glider wings, body, cockpit, and tail fins are included separately so students can create their own glider design. Students may either modify the completed glider model or the individual component files to make their own glider designs. Students may use any 3D modeling software they’re comfortable with to edit the glider components. TinkerCad.com is a popular, free 3D modeling application that most students will find easy to use. Regardless of which 3D modeling software the students use, they should be encouraged to understand how 3D designers use similar software to create digital models of objects. Printing and Assembling the Glider After the files are ready to print, students should import them into the 3D slicing software. The complete glider is designed to print within a 120 mm x 120 mm x 120 mm print volume. The model could be scaled, but any changes in scale could affect the fit of the components. Once the slicing software has prepared the printing instructions, all of the glider components should be printed and carefully removed from the printing surface. Check all components for excess material or unwanted strings across the component surfaces. Smooth, clean surfaces will yield the best results. Depending on the tolerances of your 3D printer, the glider cockpit and tailfin may require slight trimming or filing to fit into the slots in the glider’s body. Carefully measure the component, remove small amounts of material with a knife, and test for fit. Remove more material and refit if needed. The glider wings should be flexible enough to bend and shape to fine-tune how the wing and tail surfaces affect the glider’s flight. A simple launcher file is also included. After printing the launcher, insert a rubber band into the launcher’s hole, then loop the free end of the rubber band through the end of the band that was inserted into the hole. Pull the free end of the band tight so the band is secured to the launcher handle. Flying the Glider and Testing Its Design Efficiency Students should observe basic safety procedures when flying their gliders. The gliders should never be launched towards others. Students should also keep in mind the gliders may fly and turn unexpectedly, and only test the gliders in safe, open areas. The glider may be launched by hand or with a rubber band launcher. Launching by hand is fast and easy, but produces less consistent flights. To use the launcher, insert the glider’s tail hook (located underneath the glider cockpit) into the rubber band. Hold the launcher handle in one hand and the end of the glider body in the other. Pull the glider back while extending the launcher handle until the rubber band is taunt. Quickly releasing hold of the glider body should send it flying. Each student should launcher their glider several times and record the distance flown for each. An average of the flight distances can be used to compare which glider designs had the greatest efficiency. Additional Ideas Once all of the glider designs have been tested, students could be allowed to redesign their gliders. They should consider which designs performed the best and worst, and use that evaluation to help redesign their own gliders. Once the second round of gliders has been tested, ask the students to discuss why they made the changes they made. Also, have them discuss how the overall glider performance changed in the second round of testing. Students can also redesign the launcher handle. The included launcher design is intentionally basic, but students may wish to design and print their own launchers. Students could test multiple launcher designs with their gliders, and compare average flight distances to measure which launcher designs were more effective.

description.text:
This is yet another enclosure for VU2ESE Ashhar Farhan's BitX40 transceiver. It's different from other boxes because it's ergonomically more efficient--the volume and tuning dials are positioned for ease of use and the speaker is tilted up towards the operator's head. It's small and has a much larger heat sink to accommodate 100% duty cycle transmissions that digital modes require.

This is a slightly revised version; I've included cut-away supports for the bottom plate inset for the top case and made some of the holes a little larger to reduce the amount of post-printing work that was required.

When I print it in PET, the top case requires about 10 hours and uses about 85g of filament. The bottom prints in about 3 hours and uses around 25g of filament.

Notes:

These models have supports built-into the model geometry where required. They can be easily knocked out after printing. I've printed these parts successfully in PLA and PET. If you print with PET, a 3mm brim on some parts may be helpful in ensuring bed adhesion during printing.

Parts & Assembly

The model is composed two halves for the case: a base that holds the circuit board and the bottom feet using M3 screws, and a top which holds the Raduino, speaker and user interface items. There are also four chamfered holes on the base that attach the top case using M3 flat head screws. The base is also marked "FRONT" and "BACK" for proper positioning of the top case and the board. The bottom feet can additionally be fitted with silicone rubber feet.

The volume on/off pot and tuning pot that come in the BitX40 kit will fit but their shafts require trimming so the vol and tuning knobs will fit. The Vol knob is nylon and can be trimmed using a knife, but I had to use a Dremel grinder to cut down and dress the shaft of the Tuning pot. You should cut the length of the shaft to about 15mm and flatten about 10mm of that. Use caution to ensure that when you are cutting and grinding that you don't burn out the bearings of the pot. Alternatively, you can use a pot from your own junk box.

The top case is attached to the base using 4mm threaded brass inserts that are pushed into holes at the corners of the top case -- the earlier version had holes for 5mm inserts. If you only have 5mm inserts, you'll have to ream them larger using a hand drill. Use M3 flat-head screws. You can easily embed the inserts into the thermoplastic using a soldering iron that's just hot enough to melt it into the plastic. Google "Installing threaded inserts into 3d printed parts" to see how it's done.

The lower edge of the LCD module of the Raduino angles into a slot and then the LCD screen can be pushed flush through the hole on the front of the case. My design is meant to allow it to be affixed to the inside of the top case with small self-tapping screws, but when I printed it in blue translucent PET, there was insufficient area to support screws, so I ended up hot gluing the LCD module to the case and using screwed standoffs between the LCD and the Arduino modules to hold them in place.

You can also use hot glue to fix the a 65mm dia. speaker over the grille area. Mine was recovered from an old clock radio.

Because I intend to use my BitX40 on JT-65 and WinLink, I needed to replace the small heatsink over the final TX transistor with one that would allow it to handle the 100% duty cycle that digital modes usually demand. I bought a "DIY Cooler Aluminum Heatsink Heat Sink Chip 1002510mm for IC LED Power Transistor" at Aliexpress. I fastened it to the box with small nylon zip ties.

A recent addition that is not reflected in the renderings but is included in the model: a hole on the right behind the tuning control for a Function button to allow the VFO to be tweaked for more precise tuning. I replaced the stock firmware with CO7WT Pavel's -- I highly recommend it.

In his BitX40 instructions, Farhan mentions that you can use one of the small earphone style audio jacks for headphones, so that when you plug in the headphones it cuts out the speaker, but leaves out specific instructions "as an exercise to you". I found a circuit that worked for me.

the gcode is pre programmed for the CR-10 in sequential print mode. Load. Print.

title: Minimalist version of Wanhao i3 V2(.1) Ultimate Glass Bed Holder

description.text:
I thought the Wanhao i3 V2 Ultimate Glass Bed Holder https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2141364 was brilliant and made one in ABS.
Worked great but over time started warping and stretching through the crossbars until they were in the way and preventing fine bed level adjustments. I then noticed the only functional areas were the corners, which also happened to be the coolest parts when the bed was being heated, so if the corners were to be altered to be stand alone then the problem mine developed would be eliminated.
So I removed the cross braces, added spokes to brace against the upper section of the springs with the area touching the springs shorted than the lock nut holding the centre screw secure and keeping the upper half of the spring in place so as to not interfere much with the spring and leveling of the bed.
Finally I printed these in PETG for added heat resistance. Since I abandoned ABS for PETG, my bed is heated to a maximum of 75 Celcius, and no deformation has taken place.
Will add photos, just haven't gotten to taking them yet.
You will need hardware. This is identical to what is listed in the Wanhao i3 V2 Ultimate Glass Bed Holder page: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2141364, and I really recommend you refer to that thingy for guidance.

title: Proline dishwasher wheel and clip

description.text:
This is a bottom tray replacement total wheel for a Proline model FDP48ASL-E dishwasher. Two wheels disapeared under unclear circumstances.

A total wheel comes in 2 parts : the wheel itself and the clip.
After printing the two parts, first the clip is inserted into the wheel, then the whole part is set on the tray (see pictures).

First I designed both parts "as it", but I was not very happy with the supports that were automatically created by the slicer (Cura). So I decided to design the models with supports included.

This is why there are two versions of the models :

  • wheel and clip "as it", without support. If you choose to print these models, you have to set the slicer for supports creation.

  • wheel and clip with supports included. If you choose to print these models, take care to uncheck the support creation in the slicer software. After printing, remove the supports (no tool needed). Supports are compatible with 0.2 maximum layer height (vertical distance to the object is 0.2 mm). Thickness of the supports is 0.4 mm (size of my nozzle).

For printing, I used ABS because of the hot working environment (hot washing and drying). I don't recommend PLA for this reason.
I used 0.2 mm layer height because I did not care for a perfect look but you can make it nicer using less than 0.2.

Comments welcome.

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

Infill:

100

nozzle size 0.4 mm
layer height 0.2 mm
3 shells
Brim 5 lines (prevent warping)

ABS - nozzle 235 °C - Bed 90 °C

Models with supports included

Remove the supports :
clip : just peel off the 2 thin supports around the upper part of the clip.
wheel : just break the supports on the lower part of the wheel.

Assembling the clip and the wheel

Take care to insert the clip on the right side of the wheel (if wrong, impossible to remove without breaking the clip). See picture.

Set the clip-and-wheel on the tray

By pushing firmly the tray side into the open hole of the clip.
